Rating: 3
I made this for Christmas and then again tonight. For Christmas, I boiled the orange juice and soaked dried tart cherries instead of cranberries, but the orange juice took the tartness away, so I didn't bother to soak the dried fruit this time and used the cranberries instead of the cherries. It worked better - chewier, tarter. I also borrowed a friend's microplane and that worked great for the zest. I was worried about the zest being overwhelming (I usually hate zest in food - so unpleasantly chewy and bitter), but the dressing was, both times, quite mild and pleasant. I used some chardonnay vinegar I got from a Michigan winery and it was lovely. I bought candied pecans from Trader Joe's so I wouldn't have to bother with toasting pecans (plus I love candied pecans!). The first time I made this salad, I mixed the dressing, orange slices, and the cherries together, but it is hard to dress the salad properly with all the large hunks of stuff getting in the way. So this time I only put the cranberries in, but then realized they might soak up all the liquid and leave me with little dressing (as I hadn't plumped them up with the orange juice soaking step), so I fished them out again. I used a boxed baby greens mix (Newman's) for the salad, then threw on the cranberries, then dressed it, then put on the orange slices and pecans. It looked lovely and tasted very bright and pleasant. If you only have to mess with getting zest and carving out slices of orange, the salad is pretty simple.

